Subsequently, the influence of the concentration of the obtained Y-CDs on their fluorescent intensity at 560 nm was investigated (Fig. S2). As the concentration of the Y-CD solution increased from 5 to 30 μg/mL, the fluorescent intensity at 560 nm initially increased before reaching its maximal value at 10 μg/mL. Thus, the concentration of the Y-CD solution was chosen to be 10 μg/mL. Then, pH effects on the fluorescence intensity of Y-CD solution were analyzed. Results indicated that fluorescence intensity of Y-CDs recorded a slight change within the broad pH range of 4.0–9.2, showing that pH within this range has little effect on Y-CD fluorescence intensity (Fig. 5
                        ). We therefore selected a solution pH value of ~6 to monitor CD fluorescence intensity (10 μg/mL), in which HCrO4− and CrO4
                        2− coexist [47]. Subsequently, the stability of as prepared CDs was tested by measuring the fluorescent intensity at 560 nm and 430 nm in 20 mM buffer at pH 6.0 in daylight for 12 h. As shown in Fig. S3, a negligible change in fluorescent intensity could be observed during the scanning process at room temperature, indicating that the Y-CDs were stable under long-term daylight.
